title: queued_message_interrupt_token ignores explicit "stop" commands
---
When a user sends an explicit "stop" while the agent is busy, `session_core.ml` queues the message and sets `queued_message_interrupt_token`. This token is designed NOT to interrupt the normal agent loop (see comment at session_core.ml:515–520). The agent loop in `agent.ml` checks it but continues looping, relying on the LLM to interpret the injected prompt "unless it explicitly asks you to stop or change course."

However, the postmortem for session teams:personal:a:1JPVF... shows the LLM received this prompt and still looped on `backlog bug` tool calls (exit codes 0 and 1, same help output) 5+ times after the user said "stop". The `queued_message_interrupt_token` provided no enforcement.

Structural fix: detect unambiguous stop/pause/wait commands in queued inbound messages and treat them as a real interrupt (e.g., `Agent.restart_interrupt_token` or a dedicated `hard_stop_interrupt_token`) rather than the soft `queued_message_interrupt_token`. 

Suggested approach:
1. In `session_core.ml` `queue_inbound_message` or in `session_turn.ml` before `inject_messages`, detect if the queued message text is exactly (or clearly) "stop", "pause", "wait", "cancel", etc.
2. If so, set a hard interrupt (or `restart_interrupt_token`) instead of `queued_message_interrupt_token`, so the agent loop actually stops.
3. Alternatively, wire `inject_messages` in `session_turn.ml` to check for stop commands in the queued messages before injecting them, and trigger a real stop if found.

Files to modify: `src/session_core.ml`, `src/session_turn.ml`, `src/agent.ml`.

